::USGOV-U01-L04-Q01::What does citizenship mean? {
~Avoiding all public responsibilities#Incorrect. Citizenship includes responsibilities, not avoiding them.
~Having power over all laws#Incorrect. Citizenship does not mean controlling all laws.
=Being a member of a country with rights and responsibilities#Correct. This is the lesson definition of citizenship.
~Only voting in elections#Incorrect. Voting is one example of participation, not the full definition of citizenship.
}

::USGOV-U01-L04-Q02::What are rights? {
~Duties citizens must fulfill#Incorrect. Duties describe responsibilities, not rights.
~Penalties for not following laws#Incorrect. Penalties are not rights.
~Types of government authority#Incorrect. Rights are not forms of authority.
=Freedoms and protections given to citizens#Correct. Rights are freedoms and protections.
}

::USGOV-U01-L04-Q03::What are responsibilities? {
=Duties citizens are expected to fulfill#Correct. Responsibilities are duties such as following laws and contributing to society.
~Optional actions citizens never need to consider#Incorrect. Responsibilities are expected duties, not optional ideas.
~Freedoms protected by law#Incorrect. That describes rights, not responsibilities.
~Government services provided by cities and states#Incorrect. Government services are not the same as citizen responsibilities.
}

::USGOV-U01-L04-Q04::Which example best shows civic participation? {
~Ignoring elections and community issues#Incorrect. Ignoring public issues is not civic participation.
=Voting in an election and staying informed#Correct. Voting and staying informed are clear examples of civic participation.
~Avoiding all laws that seem inconvenient#Incorrect. Avoiding laws is not responsible civic behavior.
~Letting others make every public decision#Incorrect. Civic participation means being involved, not withdrawing completely.
}

::USGOV-U01-L04-Q05::Why is civic responsibility important? {
=It helps society function and supports the common good#Correct. The lesson explains that civic responsibility helps society function effectively.
~It removes the need for rights#Incorrect. Civic responsibility does not replace rights.
~It only matters during elections#Incorrect. Civic responsibility includes many actions beyond elections.
~It allows citizens to ignore community needs#Incorrect. Civic responsibility involves supporting, not ignoring, community needs.
}
